  "doc_id": "48640",
  "text": "PCP is an important aspect of differentiation when cells acquire a coordinated polarization within the plane of a tissue. PCP is regulated by an evolutionary highly conserved signaling pathway initially discovered in Drosophila [CITATION_1] Goodrich and Strutt, 2011) . The central elements of this regulatory system are the core PCP genes, including frizzled ( fz), dishevelled (dsh), Van Gogh (Vang) (also known as strabismus, stbm), prickle ( pk), and flamingo ( fmi) (also known as starry night, stan) [CITATION_2] Maung and Jenny, 2011) . In addition to planar polarization, the PCP factors are also involved in the regulation of several aspects of CNS development, including axonal guidance, both in Drosophila and vertebrates Senti et al., 2003; Goodrich, 2008; [CITATION_3] Tissir and Goffinet, 2010) , but the molecular effectors of the core PCP module during neuronal differentiation remain elusive.",
